content: We have been speaking of many great masters in previous lessons.
We have also mentioned the best Swedish player Stefan Karlsson many times.
I hope he will teach us a lesson in the future, too.
Last Saturday, Stefan and Irene Karlsson were at my place, we we studied renju together.
It was fun, the meeting ended at 4am!
hehe, it was very sober meeting.
we will analyse together the game that Stefan and I played 2 weeks ago, in Tallinn Open.
It is very interesting variant, and there are many unanswered questions
I hope our teamwork will give some answers to them.
tallin open results are available as a renlib library?
Before we begin, lets warm up.
Before, luwenzhe, scm2000, SamSite, Xespok, fallnavy, slamduk, leto, virag, killer21st, weigui, Red_Zombie, HEX77, yun_shou, sosei, mayhem, yyfcsd, mikn1, ouyang, whte, shuwang.
Stefan, without surprise, opened d11 opening.
no switch to d7 this time
My plan was to play all games as white in that tournament,
but finally, I played 6 white and 1 black game.
It is because Rauni Lillemets did not swap in i11.
yes may be renju future is white favor
It depends on style, and mood.
In match with Nakamura, I played all games as black
The first 12 moves do not require comments.
These variants are something that every renju player knows.
he also used to play another 11th a lot.
Maybe recently he feels more confident about upper 11th.
The statistics shows an important trend - white is winning more and more games here.
Which soon puts the whole black tactics under question.
Actually, it used to be very good for white in old times,
but some years ago, some players started to play it again,
and in confusing times, black was quite successful,
however, now that most players are catching up with optimal theories,
it was played a lot in email WC 2003
there is not much black can do here anymore.
However, in my game with Stefan, I wanted to practice another idea.
Because the tournament is a good time to test some ideas, against strong players.
But here, the players split into two groups - fans of left block and fans of roght block
which move would you use here? left or right stop?
typical east country plotics :) left wing :)
there is more possibilities of black
I am not sure, which is better for white.
But I wanted to test the active variant.
So I chose one branch of the left style.
Here, it is possible to play more calmly,
but I continued the active variant.
Where should black stop it? up or down?
everybody waits for yy, then copy :)
Who can show win, say me
would've taken me couple weeks to see..
So, the 21st move should be to the bottom.
I'm still unable to detect any frbidden  traps :-(
Stefan, was thinking long time over move 21,
and then finally chose lower stop.
My next move was a three.
I played fast, because I had planned that I will try this variant.
Now, for 23rd move, he thought even longer.
He had totally spent over 1 hour by then.
where to block? up or down? :))
Does black have VCF threat now?
you had a good idea Before
but you just give black more stones
But both lower and right sides are active for black.
So, I think there is not much choice for white here.
White has to spend its resources to defend.
Now, i12 helps to defend pretty much.
I had briefly analysed it before,
but I was not so sure about the outcome.
The right side looks a bit dangerous,
but white has several tactical options.
i remembered we analyzeed it with team.
the trouble is, in this case, white will have no "own" area at all
which means, white can only lose or draw
but maybe its too soon to say
white's only chance is black's mistake
maybe the way I played, was poor
if the variant I used loses,
I think white should change the whole variant,
you can say me, and try, anyone
guests dont play moves on class board, sorry
there is analyze function for that...
if 26-40 in RT styke,could black win?
killer, we will see it soon
black has positional control all over
well, maybe this is not so important
This 33 move has been most of my concern.
Other than that, white is fine here.
Stefan chose this 33rd move in the game.
To prove, whether this is win or not,
we only have short time here.
White got the chance to be more active now.
By the 36th move, I felt this position is safe already.
I thought quite long time here.
then I might lose tempo in the end.
and that is not good, because black already has good e6 stone.
something like that, may become troublemsome
So I chose this 40th move, to keep up active play.
after long thinking, I could not find win.
black can have even more material
After short thinking, I realized, that despite the black material,
sorry, it was my idea too :-)
So he defended, having just a few time left.
In a hurry, he still made a great move.
I was thinking long time about overline attack.
but after long thinking, I still found winning 48th move.
and from here, VCT for any move.
He played in a hurry already,
so move 48 created left win and right win
this seemed the only hope to save from direct loss
and white can attack joyfully everywhere
We did not analyse seriously here
but white has so many great ideas
ok who wants to try white
else, your hint takes the joy away from player
So, this variant was a good surprise for my opponent.
It took a great risk here,
because I had not analysed much about active 33
but such small tournament was a good place to test some moves
of course, in case of WC, one should never use this variant as white without making very clear first
So, your duty will be to analyse it,
whether it is black win or not
Let us have last check then

mikn1, Xespok, Before, luwenzhe, SamSite, Red_Zombie, virag, yyfcsd, mayhem, Intotherenju, slamduk, Ikon, killer21st, scm2000, weigui, fallnavy, sosei, concord2497, yun_shou, shuwang, leto, jamphen, whte, ouyang.
it was a really nice and interesting lesson, thank you, Ando!!
The right side 16 is much more peaceful
hereby, we will end the lesson.
Maybe this 14 will soon fade out of theory
and people will mostly play here
